        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Liuij Stylus: pra[e]sertim in Concionibus.
                        Nulla[e] Latina[e], Gra[e]ca[e]úe orationes, vel accurata lectione, vel exquisito delectu digniores, 
                        quàm Liuianae conciones; à Perionio in artificiosum quendam ordinem redacta[e]. Undè, 
                        cum orationibus vacat aut Legendis, aut imitandis, aut etiam a[e]mulandis, nullas iam malim, quàm has,
                        aut illas Liuianas; tam sententia acres, quàm elocutione limatas. Nihil pla[e]runq[ue] vel neruosiùs 
                        pressum, vel viuidiùs expressum. Vt sa[e]pè ipse Atticismus hîc superari videatur. Tam 
                        prudenter politus hic stylus: modò fusus splendidè; modò strictus argutè; modò 
                        scitè temperatus: sa[e]pè adamantinus; semper gemmans, aut florens. Ni Ca[e]sarem, Sallustium, 
                        Virgilium intimè nosset, mirarer tam nitidam pariter, solidamq[ue] componendi formulam: non magis 
                        illuminatam, quàm seriam; nec minùs subtilem, quàm ornatam. Valdè etiam placent 
                        qua[e]dam rotunda, et arguta dicta: quasi Laconica apophthegmata. Nec unq[uam] fermè deficit varietas: 
                        nec vigor ferè uspiam flaccescit. Mea adhuc ha[e]c Censura: nec in aliam sum, uel facilè ducendus, 
                        uel solicitè trahendus sententiam.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Livy"/>
                    <person name="Joachim Perion"/>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                    <person name="Sallust"/>
                    <person name="Virgil"/>
                    <book title="T. Livii Patavini Conciones"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>
                Livy's style, particularly in the speeches.
                There are no Latin or Greek orations that deserve more precise reading, or more special enjoyment than Livy’s 
                speeches, raised to some literary rank by Joachim Perion. Therefore, when I have leisure for reading, imitating or 
                emulating speeches, I prefer no others to those of Livy, which are as sharp in judgement as they are polished 
                in expression. Nothing is more vigorously compressed or livelier expressed, so that often even Atticism 
                seems to be surpassed. His style is so sensibly polished, here marvelously copious, there ingeniously tight,
                elsewhere skilfully balanced; often adamantine, always brilliant or bright. If he had not been intimately 
                acquainted with Caesar, Sallust, and Virgil, I would marvel at such an equally refined and firm form of writing,
                not just clear but also serious, and no less precise than rich. Very pleasing also are several well-turned and 
                witty statements, almost Laconic maxims. Variety is almost never lacking and its vigor hardly ever falters. This
                is my judgment so far and I am not easily brought or restlessly drawn to another opinion.
                <!-- JE: I've tweaked this translation for the sake of idiom. -->
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
